{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642620"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17958"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.24,0.04,0.66,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10672"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63663"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24861"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old man presents with double vision. His symptoms are particularly noticeable when he tries to look hard to the right (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"A problem with which one of the following cranial nerves is responsible for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["II","III","IV","VI","VII"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings suggest a dysfunction of the right lateral rectus muscle, which is responsible for abducting the eye. The photograph shows that he is unable to fully abduction the right eye. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral rectus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerve VI\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the abducens nerve. Dysfunction of this nerve can lead to an inability to move the eye laterally, resulting in horizontal diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve III\u003C/strong\u003E, the oculomotor nerve, innervates most of the other extraocular muscles, including the superior, inferior, and medial rectus muscles, as well as the inferior oblique muscle. It also controls the levator palpebrae superioris muscle, which elevates the eyelid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve IV\u003C/strong\u003E, the trochlear nerve, innervates the superior oblique muscle, which is responsible for intorsion and depression of the eye when it is adducted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve VII\u003C/strong\u003E, the facial nerve, is primarily responsible for facial expression and does not control any of the extrinsic muscles of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve II\u003C/strong\u003E, the optic nerve, is responsible for vision and does not control any eye movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The extrinsic muscles of the eye are controlled by cranial nerves III, IV, and VI.","Cranial nerve III (oculomotor nerve) innervates most of the extraocular muscles.","Cranial nerve IV (trochlear nerve) innervates the superior oblique muscle.","Cranial nerve VI (abducens nerve) innervates the lateral rectus muscle."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. 